content:
Chapter: Electric Field Intensity and Potential due to an Electric Dipole

(i) On Axial Line

Electric field intensity, $E = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}\frac{2pr}{(r^2 - a^2)^2}$

If $r &gt;&gt; 2a$, then $E = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}\frac{2p}{r^3}$

Electric potential, $V = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}\frac{p}{(r^2 - a^2)}$

$$

\begin{array}{c}

\begin{array}{c}

-q \\

A

\end{array}

\begin{array}{c}

\rightarrow \\

O

\end{array}

\begin{array}{c}

+ q \\

B

\end{array}

\begin{array}{c}

\rightarrow \\

E

\end{array}

\begin{array}{c}

\rightarrow E \\

E_0

\end{array}

\begin{array}{c}

\rightarrow \\

E_1

\end{array}

\end{array}

$$

If $r &gt;&gt; 2a$, then $V = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}\frac{p}{r^2}$

(ii) On Equatorial Line

Electric field intensity

$$

E = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0} \frac{p}{(r^2 + a^2)^{3/2}}

$$

If $r &gt;&gt; 2a$, then

$$

E = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0} \frac{p}{r^3}

$$

Electric potential, $V = 0$

![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)

Handbook of Physics

(iii) At any Point along a Line Making  $\theta$  Angle with Dipole Axis

Electric field intensity  $E = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}\frac{p\sqrt{(1 + 3\cos^2\theta)}}{r^3}$

![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)

Electric potential  $V = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}\frac{p\cos\theta}{(r^2 - a^2\cos^2\theta)}$

If  $r &gt; 2a$ , then  $V = \frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_0}\frac{p\cos\theta}{r^2}$

